}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 94-96.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Who speaks these words, the angel of Humility or the poet?  The debate has been \softline
active for years.  Marcello Aurigemma ("Il Canto XII del }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ," in }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Nuove letture \softline
dantesche}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , vol. IV [Florence: Le Monnier, 1970]), pp. 123-25, after reviewing various arguments, \softline
opts for the notion that it is Dante who speaks.  The closeness of the sentiment expressed here to \softline
that found at }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  X.121-129 (with its 'angelic butterfly' at verse 125), which issues from \softline
the poet's mouth, would seem to support the idea that it is the poet who speaks here as well.  \softline
Nonetheless, we have followed Petrocchi's punctuation, and it does not allow for the attribution \softline
of these lines to the poet.  The main arguments for doing so are that for Dante to allude so clearly \softline
to his own special election is, even for him, a bit bold; further, the lack of indication of a second \softline
and new speaker and the abruptness that would result from such a shift both argue for Petrocchi's 
view; still further, only the angel could state as a fact that so few are chosen to rise this far.  On \softline
the other hand, no other angel makes comments about humankind that are as harsh as these, since \softline
the seven angels of purgatory are celebrating the continuing ascent of this special visitor to the \softline
mountain.  Perhaps the fullest, fairest, and most helpful gloss to the passage is found in Poletto's \softline
commentary (1894) to these verses, and he, after careful debate, comes down on the side of the \softline
attribution of these words to the angel.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
